(41, 1, '2014-08-01 12:54:39', '2014-08-01 17:54:39', 'Okay, so you\'ve done your market research (hopefully), put together an plan, cooked up your ground-breaking idea, and you are ready to build your website or app so you can get this show on the road. Also you know that you don\'t want to spend months or years learning how to code, so you\'ve decided to leverage the talents of a developer.\r\n\r\nYou can\'t quite afford the hot-shot developers at the agency downtown so you instinctually go to Craigslist or Elance and begin your search for the "right" freelance developer. You might even ask some friends for some contacts. You find someone who seems good enough and has a "great" rate. Hooray! You\'re good to go. You send the guy the deposit funds to start and the anticipation of the glorious outcome continues to build.\r\n<h3>The Aftermath</h3>\r\nSix months and thousands of dollars later, you still have no product to ship. Or if you do, the product is so buggy and expensive to maintain that your baby business is already fading fast. You\'re getting words like API, SQL, SSL, Gem, UX, SEO, Validation, Backend, Frontend, Analytics and CMS thrown at you. But you are totally in the dark about what\'s going on or what your contractor is actually doing. You\'re getting surprise invoices left and right for thousands of dollars. You have very few customers, if any, and the one\'s you do have are very unhappy. You\'re grand idea that was supposed to make you a fortune (or at least a living) is now an endless nightmare hobby that has sucked all the passion (and money) from you.\r\n\r\nYou now ask yourself, "Did I hire the right guy to do this?". It would seem like the catastrophe happened either because your idea was bad or because it was executed poorly by your developer. The self-centeredness in us all goes right to the developer as the scapegoat. "It\'s definitely their fault" (Even though the odds are your idea had some holes in it too). But the truth is, whether you blame your idea or your hired gun (or both), this all could\'ve been avoided by you. You already know this, but I\'ll say it anyway. You are ultimately responsible for the success of your product. That\'s the good and bad side of being in business. Sobering but true.\r\n<h3>Picking up the pieces</h3>\r\nThere\'s no way around it. Failing sucks. But what sucks more is failing and not being able to pin-point exactly why you failed. Or what to do next time to prevent failing the same way. Fact is, you could start over with a different developer and end up with the same result. FML. If insanity is doing the same thing over and over but expecting a different result, then you are riding the crazy train. In the end it feels more like a curse than a single unfortunate event. But it\'s time to take a stand.\r\n\r\nIs this you? Have you already been through a few developers on a few different projects with no success? Have developers and freelancers left a bad taste in your mouth? Never know what to expect? Always getting surprise bills for way more than you thought? Are you about to give up on your dream and write your ambitions off like everyone else?\r\n<h3>How it should be</h3>\r\nImagine it is simple to launch your product quickly and on budget. You are launching your app without a hitch, minimal bugs, and bringing joy to your customers. You are making a profit quickly, instead of waiting years to recoup your investment. You love working with your developer because she is an invaluable asset to your business. No "surprise invoices". She fills you in on exactly what is going on. Most of all, imagine it was easy to find her because you knew where to look, what signs to look for and how to hire her the right way. Is this world possible? Or is this person more like a unicorn?\r\n<h3>The secret</h3>\r\nWell, it turns out that hiring a great developer is not a pipe dream. The secret is that it takes a good coder to hire a good coder. In other words, pay an expensive "rockstar" coder to help you vet a developer for your project.\r\nThink about it. You don\'t know where to find quality developers. You don\'t know what good or bad code looks like. You don\'t know what traits and practices reveal a good developer or a bad one. You aren\'t sure which skills they need to have, i.e. design, frontend, backend, etc, etc. You don\'t know how to prove that they have the skills they say they do. Freelancers can just throw words and acronyms at you to impress you and get the sale (I\'ve seen it). You aren\'t even sure which platform to use, and hence what type of developer you\'ll need. There are so many unknowns in this situation, I can\'t even list them all. Why not leverage the brain of someone who understands this world. Even if it costs you a pretty penny to buy a couple session hours, it will be well worth it in the long run.\r\n\r\nFamous (or internet famous) developers are everywhere shipping products and living your dream. You can\'t justify hiring one of those guys at hundreds of dollars per hour for an entire project, but you could swing hiring them for one or two hours to help get you going in the right direction. Even if you pay a few hundred dollars for an hour of their time, this could save you thousands of dollars and potentially years of wasted time.\r\nWhere do you start?\r\n\r\nDo this. Find a "rockstar" developer on the web who you know without a doubt is an expert and developing things similar to your product. This is who you would hire to build your product if money was no object. But remember, you\'re just hiring her for 2 hours. Her hourly rate will be expensive. Email her and then try calling her up. Pay for an hour long session before you look for candidates to get an idea of who you want to find. Then pay her for another session again after you have at least 5 candidates and are ready to pull the trigger.\r\n\r\nI could (and should) write a whole book on this, but here is a quick run-down of what to do.\r\n<h4>1. Prepare: Get your stuff together</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Do market research online to make sure your idea is worth pursuing and there are people ready to buy your product</li>\r\n	<li>Make rough sketches of your product</li>\r\n	<li>Figure out the budget for your product</li>\r\n	<li>Figure out a rough timeline</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>2. First Session: Questions</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>What skills should my developer have to do this project?</li>\r\n	<li>What are the basic process needed for a project like this? (i.e. design &gt; frontend &gt; backend &gt; testing &gt; launch)</li>\r\n	<li>Which Platform/Language do you recommend for this project? i.e. Rails, Wordpress, Shopify, Magento, Objective C, Django, .NET, Java, etc. (You want to use the right platform for the project, not just whatever platform your developer happens to use)</li>\r\n	<li>For what reasons do you recommend this platform?</li>\r\n	<li>Where can I find good (insert platform) developers? Do you have a developer you would recommend?</li>\r\n	<li>Ask any questions about anything you don\'t understand. Ask as many questions as you can!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>3. Candidates: Find &amp; Interview</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Decide whether you want a remote developer or if you want to limit yourself to local</li>\r\n	<li>Find them online or from recommendation</li>\r\n	<li>Email them and request an estimate of cost &amp; time for your project. (Attach sketches)</li>\r\n	<li>Also ask to see their work (pay attention to their writing skills).</li>\r\n	<li>Call them. Ask them some questions that require an in depth response. (pay attention to their verbal communication skills)</li>\r\n	<li>Look at their GitHub.com account to see what "open source" projects they love to work on</li>\r\n	<li>Ask for references to call (I know this is old school but it works).</li>\r\n	<li>Ask references if they meet deadlines and budgets.</li>\r\n	<li>Years of experience don\'t matter</li>\r\n	<li>Don\'t be fooled by the hourly rate. It means nothing. Ask them a range of hours that it would take to complete project so you can get an idea of total cost.</li>\r\n	<li>Rule out anyone who is bad at communicating</li>\r\n	<li>Rule out anyone who is not excited to teach you about things you don\'t understand</li>\r\n	<li>Rule out anyone who you wouldn\'t enjoy interacting with a lot</li>\r\n	<li>Rule out anyone who is not passionate.</li>\r\n	<li>Narrow down to 3-5 developers</li>\r\n	<li>Meet them each in person for 30 minute interviews to get a feel for them</li>\r\n	<li>Compile all profiles, contact info, previous work, github urls, etc for each candidate, and email for your rockstar. (Make it easy to quickly move through their work and see what caliber of developer they are)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>4. Second Session: Questions</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>After viewing all candidates, which developer would be best for my project?</li>\r\n	<li>For what reasons is this developer the best choice?</li>\r\n	<li>Should I go along with _____\'s pricing and billing methods or propose a different payment structure?</li>\r\n	<li>My gut is telling me Bob, do you think he is a good pick?</li>\r\n	<li>Why or why wouldn\'t Bob be a good pick?</li>\r\n	<li>Ask every valuable question that comes to your mind.</li>\r\n	<li>It will be very clear at this point, and you will at least have it narrowed down to 1 or 2.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>5. Trial Run: Hire for pre-project</h4>\r\nNext hire the chosen developer for a mini-project. Regardless of who you pick, always do a pre-project if it\'s the first time working with someone. Take a small part of your large project and break it off into a mini-project that will have it\'s own budget and deadline. This is where the rubber meets the road and you can see if the developer is good to work with or not. Odds are if they\'ve been vetted by your rockstar it will be fine, but if not you can make your way down the list to the next best person.\r\n<h4>6. Make It Official: Hire to build your product</h4>\r\nNow that you\'ve completed the first pre-project and know that it\'s a good fit, it\'s time to dive in and get stuff done. You know that you can trust them. Your "rockstar" developer trusts them. Let\'s build this product! Sell it. Give customers what they are wanting and reap the benefits in the process.\r\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\nYou now have a great Ruby developer who is partnering with you on your product. She is keeping you in the know about everything and letting you know what to expect along the way. You know what her skills are and at least a little bit about everything they handle for you. You understand more than half of the acronyms now because she has been teaching you along the way. You know your using a Ruby On Rails backend platform with an API that talks to your iOS and Android app seamlessly. You also have a neutral third party who can help you decipher the state of your product when you get confused. You are able to focus on your customers now, the ones who really matter. This cohesiveness between you and your team helps your business become more profitable and helps you make better financial decisions.\r\n\r\nBut most of all, you have piece of mind because you know what is happening with your product and where you are taking this ship.', 'How to hire a developer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-01 12:54:39', '2014-08-01 17:54:39', '', 1, 'http://dev.railsvitamins.com/1-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(42, 1, '2014-08-01 12:57:23', '2014-08-01 17:57:23', 'Do you feel like your still doing web/software dev in the stoneage? Still using FTP or SVN? Ever have a client ask you to put things back how they were 2 weeks ago? Or do you have a hard time collaborating with other developers?\r\n\r\nImagine you can rewind or revert to any stage in development at the drop of a hat. And when it’s time to work on a risky or experimental feature you could get messy without affecting the main source code of the project. Imagine it is simple and straight forward to collaborate with other devs on your team without stepping on each others toes. For these and a million other reasons, you need to use Git! Git is a small but powerful tool vital to any Rails developer. If you are new to Rails and are ready to usher in a new age for yourself, it’s best to just jump on the Git bandwagon right away so you’ve got a leg to stand on.\r\n\r\nNote: Their is a distinction between Git and Github. Although related and used in tandem, it’s important to know that Git is the version control system on your local computer and Github is  a web-based hosting service. We will focus on Git\r\n\r\nHere’s a fast track to getting setup with Git:\r\n<h3>1. Open Terminal</h3>\r\nFind the application called Terminal on your Mac (or Windows Equivalent) and open it. You should see a black command-line screen once opened\r\n<h3>2. Setup Git</h3>\r\nTo setup Git on your computer, type these in the command-line ($ signifies that this is a command, don’t type the $):\r\n<pre>$ git config --global user.name “Ty Richards”</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git config --global user.name   # to confirm name saved</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git config --global user.email “me@tyrichards.com”</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git config --global user.email   # to confirm email saved</pre>\r\n<h3>3. Create New Repo</h3>\r\nTo setup a Git repo for a new project or give an existing project a repo:\r\n<pre>$ cd ~/Sites/new_project  # travel to your new project folder in terminal</pre>\r\n<pre>$ pwd   # verify that you are in that directory</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git init  # creates a new repo</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git status # to see what files are being tracked$ git add .  # adds all files in current folder)</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git commit -a -m “initial commit”  # commits all(-a) modified files and includes a message(-m)</pre>\r\n<h3>4. Do Stuff</h3>\r\nAfter every task you do you can:\r\n<pre>$ git status # to see what is being tracked and modified</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git add .</pre>\r\n<pre>$ git commit -am “Build initial scaffolding”</pre>\r\nand repeat\r\n\r\nWith this you’ll be setup and ready to go in the era of Git. At it’s best you have full control of your source code revisions and collaboration, and at worst you have a nicely documented history of revisions that have been made on the project. There are many more advanced features of Git and GitHub makes things more exciting too. With Git you also need to understand branches, remotes, and the .gitignore file, but you are at least jumpstarted into the world of Git. More on these other things later.', 'Get going with Git', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'get-going-with-git', '', '', '2014-08-05 10:22:42', '2014-08-05 15:22:42', '', 0, 'http://dev.railsvitamins.com/?p=42', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(43, 1, '2014-08-01 12:57:23', '2014-08-01 17:57:23', 'Do you feel like your still doing web/software dev in the stoneage? Still using FTP or SVN? Ever have a client ask you to put things back how they were 2 weeks ago? Or do you have a hard time collaborating with other developers?\r\n\r\nImagine you can rewind or revert to any stage in development at the drop of a hat. And when it’s time to work on a risky or experimental feature you could get messy without affecting the main source code of the project. Imagine it is simple and straight forward to collaborate with other devs on your team without stepping on each others toes. For these and a million other reasons, you need to use Git! Git is a small but powerful tool vital to any Rails developer. If you are new to Rails and are ready to usher in a new age for yourself, it’s best to just jump on the Git bandwagon right away so you’ve got a leg to stand on.\r\n\r\nNote: Their is a distinction between Git and Github. Although related and used in tandem, it’s important to know that Git is the version control system on your local computer and Github is  a web-based hosting service. We will focus on Git\r\n\r\nHere’s a fast track to getting setup with Git:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Find the application called Terminal on your Mac (or Windows Equivalent) and open it. You should see a black command-line screen once opened</li>\r\n	<li>To setup Git on your computer, type these in the command-line ($ signifies that this is a command, don’t type the $):\r\n$ git config —global user.name “Ty Richards”\r\n$ git config —global user.name   # to confirm name saved\r\n$ git config —global user.email “me@tyrichards.com”\r\n$ git config —global user.email   # to confirm email saved</li>\r\n	<li>To setup a Git repo for a new project or give an existing project a repo:\r\n$ cd ~/Sites/new_project  # travel to your new project folder in terminal\r\n$ pwd   # verify that you are in that directory\r\n$ git init  # creates a new repo\r\n$ git status # to see what files are being tracked\r\n$ git add .  # adds all files in current folder)\r\n$ git commit -a -m “initial commit”  # commits all(-a) modified files and includes a message(-m)</li>\r\n	<li>After every task you do you can:\r\n$ git status\r\n$ git add .\r\n$ git commit -am “Build initial scaffolding”\r\nrepeat</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWith this you’ll be setup and ready to go in the era of Git. At it’s best you have full control of your source code revisions and collaboration, and at worst you have a nicely documented history of revisions that have been made on the project. There are many more advanced features of Git and GitHub makes things more exciting too. With Git you also need to understand branches, remotes, and the .gitignore file, but you are at least jumpstarted into the world of Git. More on these other things later.', 'Get going with Git', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '42-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-01 12:57:23', '2014-08-01 17:57:23', '', 42, 'http://dev.railsvitamins.com/42-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
